description:
'''Evin Agassi'''{{efn|His first name is generally pronounced ''Evan'' by [[Iranian Assyrians]] and ''Ewan'' by [[Iraqi Assyrians|Iraqi]] and [[Syrian Assyrians]], with an [[Stress (linguistics)|emphasis]] on the vowels. Though Agassi's preferred pronunciation was ''Evin''.}} (25 September 1945 – 17 September 2024) was an Iranian-American Assyrian singer who had a career that spanned for over 50 years. Agassi produced over 40 albums during his career, with a majority of them being released in the 1980s and 1990s.

Possessing [[spinto]]-[[tenor]] vocals, his work generally consisted of sophisticated [[ballad]]s, [[love song]]s, [[anthem|nationalistic]] music and folk dance, with musical inspiration from [[Persian pop]] and, more recently, [[Latin pop]] genres, where he fused his art with [[Civil resistance|cultural resistance]].

One of the better-known Assyrian singers, he generally toured Australia, Europe and [[West Asia]]. The majority of his songs were written by his brother, Givergiss Agassi, both in [[Persian language|Persian]] and [[Assyrian Neo-Aramaic|Assyrian]]. His full name has also been spelled as '''Evan Aghassi'''.{{efn|Many [[Suret|Assyrian]] speakers generally use the [[voiced velar fricative]] ('gh' sound) when uttering the first consonant in his surname.}}
